Comment:
I am so sorry for your loss, Rachel.    I lost my husband to a sudden heart attack in 2005 when he was 48.  Those completely unexpected losses (car accident, heart attack) with absolutely not a minute to prepare, can really catch you off guard, but I believe our loved ones have the ability (in the strangest or most subtle of ways) to offer us the strength we need at the time. 
There was movie called Serenity, from the TV show FIREFLY (a sci-fi cowboy premise) that was premiering the night before his funeral.  So I went.  We had really been looking forward to seeing that movie, I just had to go and I felt he was there with me.  A friend had come in from out of state for the funeral, and I suppose he thought it was strange, but he went to the movie with me.  Frankly, I really needed that few hours of distraction.   We all have to do what we need to do to survive, especially during those surreal days of "putting on a funeral". üò¢You just kind of go into a "survivor" mode, you feel like you're in a trance, but you can get done everything that needs to be done.

For the past several years, Disney has been catering their movies and stories in parallel with trending identity political topics, that tend to be left-leaning and relying heavily on political-correctness. The issue I have isn't that these messages are fundamentally "bad"; it's that Disney is a corporation with the root intention to turn a profit. So they've pivoted themselves to align with trends (and political ideologies), to make themselves look "good", at the cost of good storytelling. 

In doing so, they've also patronized their core audience (like men - see She-Hulk), because that's what's trendy at the moment. For clarification, if Christianity was blowing up in America and was the "cool" trendy thing to do - Disney would pivot their storytelling to include subtle (or not-so-subtle) Christian ideologies, because they'd think this is what the audience wants. "Woke" is different than well-intentioned inclusiveness. The difference being that root of "woke" ideology if founded in virtue signaling, i.e. proving to others ones own moral superiority (or some other form of self-interest gain).

Disney is a corporation - they aren't interested in "doing the right thing". The fundamental goal of a corporation is to make as much money as possible. "Woke" is like someone volunteering at homeless shelter so they can post about it on social media, versus doing it out of the kindness of their heart. Comment:
I think the MCU was always very average movie wise.
They are extremely entertaining films. Popcorn entertainment. But they have zero substance. 

They are flicks. Not cinematic masterpieces. 
They are the same movie recycled, newly packaged, same formula, same plot, same old end of the world as cheap stakes and same old heroes band together to defeat villain. 

But the movies are still fun and good entertainment. But they are not as profound, meaningful and well directed, not as well acted and emotionally powerful as many other movies. 
Some people realized that 10 years ago. Many realized this by Civil War. And now with the next phase and Disney‚Äôs painfully obvious new money scheming ways with giving each hero own TV shows and continuing with the same old sequels of their countless franchises even the biggest, blinded fanboys realize that superhero movies are a recycled, rebooted plot with a different paint job. Thats just what I have been observing
author: @lightup6751

Comment:
¬†@lightup6751¬† - well, everybody's got an opinion. My opinion is the MCU has had unprecedented success in creating a shared universe, no one else has come close to what they've done. My wife didn't know anything about comic books back in the late 2000s and now she cries when Tony dies in Endgame. She tears up every time we watch the Guardians 3 trailer and is honestly worried about who's going to die in the film.

The MCU is made for everybody, not just comic book nerds. I'm not gonna be hypercritical about how they adapt certain storylines, I'm just happy we're getting what we're getting. Guardians has been my favorite team for a long time and I will never forget the day in 2012 when I saw the first concept images for the film. I screamed "Rocket f-ing Raccoon!!!" at the top of my lungs and my wife came running from the other end of the house to find out what I was yelling about. James Gunn made a massive success out of a talking raccoon and a walking tree. And here we are a decade later coming to the final chapter of their story. This is true movie magic, the stuff dreams are made of.

Comment:
¬†@DiscoScottie¬† 

Like you said, everybody‚Äôs got an opinion. 
I agree that the MCU and the Russo Brothers did something amazing with the multiverse. These movies live and die by the crossover gimmick. If it would have been 30 Avenger movies the series would have died after a few years. But exploring new heroes and their origin stories gives them the perfect plea to keep making movies. 
Like you said the MCU is made for everyone. Like franchises as the The Fast and the Furious as well. 
They catered the movies specifically to hit the widest spectrum of an audience. 
The movies are not deep or filmmaking masterpieces but they are entertaining. The best superhero movies of all time.
But they are still flicks and high production blockbusters. Which isn‚Äôt a bad thing at all. But I think that is undeniable. 
The plot is recycled and formulaic. There is no risk taking from the directors. No stakes. When characters die its like hey, lets use a time machine and bring everyone back. I understand that they have creative limitations because they are based on comic books that follow the same formula. That formula is entertaining too. But it has no depth. Like you said tho, its just opinions at the end of the day. To me superhero films are like fast food. Its accessible, can be tasty is popular for everyone. But its not a homemade meal put creatively put together by a chef. 
But fast food can be enjoyed by anyone of all ages and backgrounds. 
I think the MCU achieved an incredible position in the world of cinema.
There is a reason these films are not taught at film school, dont win Oscars for acting and a reason why most actors starring in them wouldn‚Äôt want their superhero gig be their peak achievement as an actor. They are not as pushed in these performances. 

I want to emphasize that I genuinely respect your opinion and I‚Äôm glad you and your wife enjoy them. I think they are good entertainment. But not really great movies considering cinema and filmmaking. 
I personally don‚Äôt think they give a deeper understanding of the human condition or really tug at our heartstring and let us relate or resonate with the characters. But I love the hype crossover, the team ups and interaction of the different heroes, the glorious CGI and epic dramatic heroics. To me those are the aspects that define this genre. I do think that most people who watch a lot of movies from blockbuster to arthouse will agree that the movies are fun flicks not cinematic masterpieces but I have no right to tell anyone what to think. After all, we all should go for what we enjoy!
author: @lightup6751

Comment:
¬†@elizabethsmith7224¬† 

I do agree. You dont have to only watch Oscar winning films or arthouse cinema. I like superhero films. But you also shouldn‚Äôt only watch blockbusters. Balance is key. MCU is like fast food. Fast food is accessible and can be enjoyed by everyone. 
But eating it everyday would ruin your health. 
Sometimes you need that home cooked meal

Comment:
¬†@theludonarrian¬† Avengers: Endgame is a 2019 American superhero film
based on the Marvel Comics superhero team the Avengers.
Produced by Marvel Studios and distributed by Walt Disney
Studios Motion Pictures, it is the direct sequel to Avengers:
Infinity War (2018) and the 22nd film in the Marvel
Cinematic Universe (MCU). Directed by Anthony and Joe
Russo and written by Christopher Markus and Stephen
McFeely, the film features an ensemble cast including Robert
Downey Jr., Chris Evans, Mark Ruffalo, Chris Hemsworth,
Scarlett Johansson, Jeremy Renner, Don Cheadle, Paul Rudd,
Brie Larson, Karen Gillan, Danai Gurira, Benedict Wong, Jon
Favreau, Bradley Cooper, Gwyneth Paltrow, and Josh Brolin.
In the film, the surviving members of the Avengers and their
allies attempt to reverse the destruction caused by Thanos in
Infinity War.
The film was announced in October 2014 as Avengers:
Infinity War ‚Äì Part 2, but Marvel later removed this title. The
Russo brothers joined as directors in April 2015, with Markus
and McFeely signing on to write the script a month later. The
film serves as a conclusion to the story of the MCU up to that
point, ending the story arcs for several main characters. The
plot revisits several moments from earlier films, bringing back
actors and settings from throughout the franchise. Filming
began in August 2017 at Pinewood Atlanta Studios in Fayette
County, Georgia, shooting back-to-back with Infinity War,
and ended in January 2018. Additional filming took place in
the Metro and Downtown Atlanta areas, the state of New York,
Scotland, and England. The official title was revealed in
December 2018. With an estimated budget of $356‚Äì
400 million, the film is one of the most expensive films ever
made.
Avengers: Endgame premiered in Los Angeles on April 22,
2019, and was released in the United States on April 26, as
part of Phase Three of the MCU. The film received praise for
its direction, acting, musical score, action sequences, visual
effects, and emotional weight, with critics lauding its
culmination of the 22-film story. The film grossed $2.798
billion worldwide, surpassing Infinity War's entire theatrical
run in just eleven days and breaking numerous box office
records, including becoming the highest-grossing film of all
time from July 2019 until March 2021. It received a
nomination for Best Visual Effects at the 92nd Academy
Awards, among numerous other accolades. A fifth and sixth
film, Avengers: The Kang Dynasty and Avengers: Secret
Wars, are scheduled to be released in 2025 and 2026. Hope that clears it up for you.

in comparison.... Spiderman. First film we had Iron Man create the Vulture, second one had Mysterio created by ... Tony Stark. Then no way home came and.... it was a cross over with Dr Strange and two other Peter's. Even Captain America and Hulk are tainted by the Stark name. Howard Stark created Captain America, and Bruce then tried to replicate the serum and became Hulk.

imagine being a fan of just one or two comics. "Oh i like the idea of Dr Strange." You watch the 1st one and like it. Then you go watch the second. "Whose this Wanda? Scarlet Witch...whats that? Viz who? Thanos??" If you got to do research and watch other films (and PAY to watch a series) just to understand another film, then the film fails on its own merit.

Comment:
Overall Great movie, Loved it.  I immediately recognized the Laika (Russian Astronaut dog) reference and was saddened by this, although this puts an optimistic spin on that story dog somehow survived to gain telekinetic powers (help from some friendly aliens?) perhaps this twist was inspired by the brilliant fan made music video for Sharon Van Ettens 'I Can't Breathe" song which on its own is already depressing enough, search for the video, "I Can't Breathe, Sharon Van Etten, Laika" 

One thing that bothered me also related to the dog was the whole bad dog thing, it was an obvious and lame set up which I saw coming a mile away, plus the whole reason the guy was saying bad dog was purely because he was jealous the dog did something better than him and was insecure, which is pretty pathetic of his character especially after the dog repeatedly lets him know how much that bothers him, only after the dog saves his life is the dog redeemed to be a 'good boy' again... That's a D*ck Move! 

And the bad guy is supposed to so smart, yet doesn't realize sometimes getting an outside perspective  or having someone who can look at problems from a different point of view can be beneficial in overcoming problems, and that different people, or creatures have different types or areas of intelligence.  If everyone was equally smart and did things in the exact same way, it would be pretty boring I think. 
Also with all that bio tech, he couldn't have fixed himself a better face? :D  Literally cut and paste is the best he's got :D

Comment:
surprisingly the best superhero movie I've watched since Endgame. I honestly thought most recsnt superhero movies failed because the genre had grown tiresome, but this movie proves otherwise.

I also like that it doesn't heavily rely on nostalgia or the now tiresome multiverse concept and just create a standalone film that stands on its own. Previous characters were sprinkled here and there, but they're not shameless fan service, and don't require previous knowledge of the other films to understand, and their parts in the movie don't feel forced. Comment:
I was really a big fan of Marvel films until I saw this... disgusting, heartless, extremely cruel movie with a lack of any humor, primitive dialogues, and a stupid boring plot. A few times during the movie I wanted to leave the cinema but I forced myself to watch THIS till the end. My wife cried and had to close her eyes every time they showed these animals being tortured. This was NOT a "Guardians of the Galaxy" movie as we knew it, but a mix of "Saw" and "The Human Centipede" and god only knows what else. Scenes with those poor animals I will probably never forget. I understand that director wanted to show how they suffer and so on, but why this was shown in such a SICK way? It was just sick and disgusting and I don't understand how anyone on this planet can enjoy watching these tortures.
Bye-bye, Marvel...
